Upon the addition of AMO to the Cu, N-CDs-Cu2+ system, the fluorescence intensity of the system exhibited a remarkable recovery. Consequently, this system proved effective as a fluorescent sensor for detecting AMO. As AMO concentration increased in the range of 0–60 μmol/L, the intensity of the Cu, N-CDs-Cu2+ system gradually restored (Fig. 4
                        A). The Fig. 4B further demonstrated a linear relationship in the quenching efficiency within the concentration ranges of 0.03–10 μmol/L and 10–35 μmol/L with AMO concentration. The corresponding linear fitting equations were calculated as (F0-F)/F0 = 0.02633[AMO] + 0.04187 (R2 = 0.994) and (F0-F)/F0 = 0.0105[AMO] + 0.2002 (R2 = 0.999). Notably, the detection limit was calculated to be 0.009115 μmol/L, showing superior sensitivity when compared to other reported methods ((Table 2
                        )).
